Passing to the first point in the defense offered by the Tuscans‚ Ι observe that the inclusion in the lease of one chance occurrence, via, loss in warfare, which was expressly mentioned because most likely to take place, does not exclude other risks which in ordinary procedure would have been mentioned. It would be more natural to regard the clause covering loss in warfare as superfluous than to suppose that a departure from the law was contemplated, because a contraet under the Law of Nations, and especially a contract with a prince, presupposes good faith. The second argument put forward by the Tuscans is worthless. The ship was not leased. It was requisitioned‚ and he who took it must make good any accident.
